<font color="#FF0000">OUR MISSION IN VIETNAM</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jun  4  6:45:44 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Art's point about the Americans who died in Vietnam is valid. But, let's not forget the destruction of Vietnam.<br><br>
Once I was at a clinic in Quang Ngai City where 50 or so civilian amputees were gathered. This made a lasting impression on me. The Vietnamese suffered greatly.<br><br>
My interest in this whole matter is in the PEOPLE of Vietnam benefitting. Remember all of the bomb craters? the defoliation? Our company went through an area that had caught fire from airstrikes - scorched earth - a great area of desolation where a jungle once thrived.<br><br>
Remember the tears and agony of people who were among the poorest in the world? I can never forget their torment. <br><br>
We talk about bad memories. The sufferings of the civilians and the harsh conditions they endured year after year trouble me more than anything. Try to imagine sleeping at night, not knowing whether or not stray rounds will take out your family. Night after night. Year after year.<br><br>
Shouldn't we bear responsibility? Before you answer an emphatic, &quot;NO!&quot;, just remember who it was that told our Vietnamese allies that they  could always count on us! Yet we abandoned them. Who is responsible for winning them to our side - then pulling the rug from under them? Who can we pass the buck to?<br><br>
If we had been able to maintain our presence in Vietnam, by achieving our objective, wouldn't we have provided the tools to rebuild the country anyway?<br><br>
No, diplomatic relations, to me, are not about helping the communists. Rather, I am glad that we will provide aid to retrieve unexploded ordnance that will enable the peasants to feel a bit safer. We will provide the tools of modernization to enable the population of Vietnam to rebuild their country - a country that was thoroughly destroyed by years of conflict. It still lies in ruins.<br><br>
This is what &quot;Americans&quot; do.<br><br>
I will never forget those Americans who gave their lives, nor will I forget those who still suffer from wounds. But, let's not forget the MILLIONS of Vietnamese who have suffered the same, unkind fate. <br><br>
If we are able to open our eyes, we will see a great deal.
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


